<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF208-107-204  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 107 204.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Nov 13 1989 v3 n46 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM bias may be systemic, panel says.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Taylor, Kymberly.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The House Government Operations Committee is conducting hearingsinto allegations that the Navy has favored IBM with awards ofm millions of dollars in computer buys.andP;  After two days of hearings,Rep John Conyers says such unethical and corrupt contractingpractices may exist in every federal agency, and legislativechanges may be needed to correct the problem.andP;  Investigatorscharge that IBM representatives have coached Navy officials on howto write contract specifications to assure an IBM win, and how touse minority-owned firms as brokers to facilitate purchase of IBMequipment.andP;  There are also charges that free training provided byIBM to Navy officials is tantamount to an illegal gratuity.andP;  IBMdenies any wrongdoing, and asserts it has simply been doing itsjob.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (investigations).andO;Topic:     United States. NavyGovernment ContractsLegal IssuesUnited States. Congress. House. Committee on Government OperationsInvestigationsDefense Contracts.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   John Conyers. (portrait)Elvin F. Easter. (portrait)Person:    Conyers, John (investigations); Easter, Elvin F. (evidence).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>